               <SHORT_DESCR>
                  <P>Short description of the assignment´s background and purpose:</P>
                  <P>In task letter 17/40, the government decided that a scheme shall be introduced with county bully ombudsmen from autumn 2018. A national mandate shall form the basis for the scheme, at the same time that there is room for local adaptations.</P>
                  <P>The bully ombudsmen shall support and guide children, pupils and parents so that their rights to a good psycho-social environment in nurseries and primary and secondary schools is ensured.</P>
                  <P>The bully ombudsmen shall, in cooperation with the pupil and apprentice ombudsmen in their county, contribute to pupils and apprentices having their rights ensured to a good psycho-social environment in sixth form education.</P>
                  <P>The bully ombudsmen shall have the following assignments:</P>
                  <P>— Support and guide children, pupils and parents in cases on psycho-social environment,</P>
                  <P>— Carry out preventive work with information to and training for children, pupils and parents,</P>
                  <P>— Create a dialogue and contribute to good multi-disciplinary follow-up after cases have been dealt with,</P>
                  <P>— Contribute to sharing documentation and experiences in the county and nationally,</P>
                  <P>— Support the pupil and apprentice ombudsmen in work on psycho-social environment. The counties are the school owners for sixth form colleges, but not for nurseries and primary and secondary schools. By limiting the bully ombudsmens' mandate to nurseries and primary and secondary schools, the ombudsmen will also, with employment and placement in the county, be independent of the owners of primary and secondary schools and nurseries. The ombudsmen will be able to prepare an annual status report that will be discussed by both the county council and the municipal councils in the county.</P>
               </SHORT_DESCR>
